hey use constraints on the co-occurrence in conjunctions of words with similar or opposite polarity to predict the prior polarity of adjectives.
    Esuli and Sebastiani (2005) consider negation in some of their experiments involving WordNet glosses.
    Takamura et al. (2005) use negation words and phrases, including phrases such as lack of that are members in our lists of polarity shifters, and conjunctive expressions that they collect from corpora.
    Esuli and Sebastiani (2006a) is the only work in prior-polarity identification to include a neutral (objective) category and to consider a three-way classification between positive, negative, and neutral words.
    Although identifying prior polarity is a different task, they report a finding similar to ours, namely, that accuracy is lower when neutral words are included.
    Some research in sentiment analysis classifies the sentiments of sentences.
